Was kind of sad to hear after I was drinking my Guinness that they had a $3 Tall Coors Light special... I guess I had to be a local, or at least just smart enough to ask "do you have any specials" to find out what they're specials are.

I enjoyed my time there... could see myself venturing here if I was a local...
Clover coffee! Attentive, skilled baristas. Tasty sandwiches. Homey atmosphere. Beer on tap. Love this place.

I think that my rating might be closer to 2 and a half, but I'll get to that in a bit.

This is in the middle of Palmer Square, and I knew that it was likely to be a little "meh." But they had a good happy hour and I just wanted to grab a light early dinner and go to bed early. 

It has a nice pub feel to it--sort-of what you would expect from an Ivy League staple. The bar is pretty and classic feeling. It had a good crowd the night I was there. I got a inexpensive glass of wine and the happy hour special quesadilla, which was good. 

My gripe? It smelled AWFUL in there. Just a really putrid stale beer/vomit smell that made you want to leave. I thought perhaps I'd get used to it, but it was really vile. The guy at the bar next to me asked me "Is it just me or...?" and I assured him that no, it was not. I guess most people didn't mind it as much, and I couldn't bring myself to ask the nice bartender "what the hell IS that?" 

I hope that was not typical of them, but I can't see myself making a beeline to go back there after that experience.

Solid bar and Princeton institution.  Right off Palmer Square with a good selection of beers and pub grub.  A few televisions with the news and/or the game on, decent seating, and workable menu.  Not going to steal the thunder of Ferry House, Elements or Teresa's, but it's a good mainstay for a quick bite and pint.

A lunch staple in Princeton, you can always find a good burger, sandwich, or salad on the menu.  Sometimes the specials are hit or miss.  Not bad for after work either - spacious enough bar to hang with some friends and have a drink.  It can get crowded at times, so you may have to wait for a table.

(staying at friend's place in Austin): Hey, is there a coffee place we can walk to?

So, I was quite pleasantly surprised that this was nearby and the local coffee spot.

Good outdoor patio. Enjoyed a number of iced coffees and lattes here while visiting Austin.

This place is pretty much a middle of the road, neighborhood favorite. It's a nice go-to if you really have no other choices or ideas on where to eat/drink (since princeton is lacking in the latter). The menu is american favorites and nothing extraordinary, but nothing particularly bad, the bar is ok- small and cramped though when crowded. 

One time, me and my friends wanted to get drinks, and one of our group wanted to eat, so we were seated in the dining area. But, since three of us weren't eating, they kicked us out into the bar area, where my friend had to eat her bowl of chili, holding it while perched on a bar stool. It was pretty ridiculous, so it's deterred me from bringing a mix group of people, ie- people who have eaten and want a drink along with people who just want to drink- it's either or! 

They have an excellent sunday brunch, however.

I go to JP's Java often to study. I really like their coffee, and sometimes they put designs and swirls in the foam! Pretty cool. Great for studying if that's what you're into. They have two very comfortable couches. Other than that, the seating is pretty sad. Also, parking is a pain. 

I can't speak to the wi fi problems people have been talking about because I've never really had an issue with the wi fi. 

Overall, just your average, run of the mill student coffee house.
I have been going here since I was a kid and I love it! The food is great and the people are nice. Try the fondue.

Not a bad place.  I've eaten here twice this week, mainly because it's open late enough to serve food until rehearsals end. 

The food is good, but overpriced.  The Cajun Mac and Cheese is really quite good.  The wait staff is generally helpful, but the servers are reluctant to seat people unless the party is complete.   this is fine if the place is packed, but in neither case was is so. 

If Princeton had a wider variety of later-night eats available I'd probably try to find something else, but this seems  to be about all that's available with the exception of Hoagie Haven after 10.00.

Definitely a great place to stop in for a quick, but a little pricey, cup of coffee when you're cruising around UT or the drag.  Their lattes are quite tastey and are topped with some of that beautiful artisan foam.  They have a nice large deck which is perfect for these mild temperatures we are lucky to have right now.  The inside has plenty of seating and some nifty art work.  This isn't the best place to crash and read or study because it can get a little loud ... and smoky outside.

Another one of my favorite coffeehouses because the patio is on the front, and not hidden in the back, a la Europe.  

They open at 6 AM Monday through Thursday, so if you're a student, or even just working in the vicinity of campus, it's a good place to stop by before you have to be in class or at the office.  The parking is decent, too.

It's on the corner of San Jacinto and Duval, so there's much to watch go by.  Even if it's just the time.
If I lived in Austin, I'd come here at least once a day.  The ambiance is wonderful.  The coffee is superb.  My double macchiato was simply delicious.  Wow!

Without the patio JP's would be just another pretentious coffee pusher (One caveat to the patio, bring headphones because as much as I love nature, a slew of Grackles chirping their ugly faces off can be a bit distracting). Yes, their Clover coffee is good, and it better be for $2.50. However, JP's identity seems to be a bit muddled...

JP's, you're a coffee shop. There's no shame in that. Your ass-worn chairs and scattered approach to design are fine, because after all, you are a coffee shop. However, you seem to have lost sight of that and have gotten into the booze trade but you aren't a bar. Even though this offering may net you a few more dollars in sales, it's not the bulk of your business. Offering beer detracts from the contemplative sanctum that a coffee house should be especially in a town with more bars than people. Furthermore, your customer service is akin to stoners operating a lemonade stand. The Barista is supposed to serve me and make me feel welcome and yet I seem to be on His schedule. Stop talking to your friends...at least while I'm waiting to PAY for something. That's great that you're trying to make plans for your 'epic' weekend, but I'm sorry, I just don't give a sh*t.

Went here to study. Nice atmosphere, quiet with funky, relaxing music, everybody's pretty much on their laptops studying. I like it. My only gripe is that I ordered a chai here and it was way expensive at almost $4 for a small considering that it was watery and didn't taste that good. Other than that though, I like the place.

I stopped here on the way into school on a saturday morning.  I got a machiato.  A machiato is really good, if the espresso shots are pulled properly.  Unfortunately, these were not.  I decided to watch the barista pull the espresso shots.  He tamped the espresso too hard for the grind.  This resulted in the water not being able to move through the espresso grounds fast enough.  Extended contact with the water results in a really bitter espresso shot.  I tried to sweeten it up, but there was no saving the flavor of this machiato.  However, i'm addicted to caffeine so I drank it anyway. 

If you come here to study, stay away from the espresso.

Been here a few times . The food here is actually pretty good. I was surprise. I've always walked by this place many times and ever gone in here. Is this a place that I have to visit? No. It is a place to get good food when you're hungry.

I HIGHLY recommend Harvard Square Shiatsu!!!  I'm a tense & active person & this massage was just what I needed to RELAX and REVIVE. The environment is inviting and comfortable, and the masseuse is very skilled & caring. I went into a deep meditative state that refreshed my mind & body. You won't find a Swedish massage, because that is not their specialty,  but if you are looking for an AMAZING SHIATSU MASSAGE EXPERIENCE come here!

I don't know what these people are talking about when they say the baristas are rude because they have been nothing but sweet and accomodating to me. Polite, quick, and good espresso drinks.

I like this place because it is close to the ECJ (my second home as a UT engineering student). So I can escape to JP's and do some work between classes while enjoying a cup of coffee outside or hidden in a corner inside. And on a nice day they open the garage door windows and the inside is just as pleasant as enjoying the outside and I don't have to worry about my notes flying away or the glare from the sun.


This is the best coffee shop near campus because it's not Starbuck's, the music is not obnoxious, they have a patio, and the coffee is yummy. Maybe I am not an expert but I like JP's and its people.

Let me come right out and say that, as a blanket statement, I hate Princeton. Never have I encountered a town more impressed with itself. I had the misfortune to live there for 6 years and let me tell you, I'm still recovering.
So, read the following review bearing this in mind.

Winberie's is a fine place to go if you want some tasty, pub-style food and don't mind slow service.  Most of the offerings are overpriced;; I don't think there's a burger on the menu that isn't $10 or more, and for no discernible reason. Sodas are almost $3! Sheesh. Bartenders are generally excellent, but be prepared for a VERY crowded bar during peak times and games. It can be extremely loud, too. Sit in the restaurant area if you want to hear yourself think.
Decor is simple and homey- think Applebee's-style framed local items and art pieces showcasing local famous folks (Einstein, Peter Benchley, yadda yadda).

Parking in Princeton is always a problem, so if you don't live within walking distance expect to pay to use one of the nearby garages. Thankfully, the rates are reasonable.

As an ME student, JPs java is the closest place I can go to get a good cup of coffee. But it is so much more than that... 

Breakfast - The tacos are amazing 
Lunch - The ham and havarti sandwich with baby spinach and caramelized onion puts any other lunch options in a 300m radius to shame.  The roast beef with brie is also a great choice. Both are served on nice focaccia bread.

And finally the coffee: I'm not a coffee snob like several people I've seen reviewing this place, but let's get real. It is good when compared to Starbucks, Texenza, Texas Traders or anything close to the engineering block. And since I practically live next door, with the punch card i get any coffee for free in a few days. The calle del copey is delicious!

As for the drawbacks,

Beer - Hmmm... Beer? Drawback?? Maybe some people don't know how to enjoy a beer without getting drunk or something..
 
I admit that seating can be scarce sometimes, but I've always found where to sit after a few minutes if not right away.

I came here a couple times for lunch and was pretty disappointed unless I was sitting at the bar.  The wait staff was basically non-existent so I would say if you want good service to sit at the bar.  

I only came here once after hours and it was your typically college crowd but it seemed a bit "stuffy" for my tastes, so I typically ended up at the Ivy.

Not bad if you can find a seat that isn't taken by someone studying.  The coffee was ok, but not worth the hassle.  I don't understand the praise for their coffee.  Just because it's better than Starbucks, doesn't make it good.

Yes, you read that right. I'm giving a high rating to a property management company. Hell hath frozen over.

But seriously, these guys are good. From my very quick move in schedule (I first viewed the apartment just a few days before I moved in, and they managed to clean and touch up the paint that quickly) to the ease of moveout, I really appreciated the hard work of Jenn and Charley and the rest of the folks here. 

When I moved in the shower was very slow to drain and within a few hours the OWNER of Cooper Brown was out to personally de-clog my shower from the last tenant. Impressive. I luckily didn't have any other maintenance issues with my apartment, but I loved that Cooper Brown was easily accessible via email and phone calls, and they always got back to me quickly when I did have questions (or when they had questions for me). Their office is conveniently located in the Biltmore so I often ended up saving my 40-whatever cents and dropping off my rent rather than mailing it, which was nice. 

At moveout, things were equally straightforward and easy. I was able to schedule a moveout inspection on my own time, and Charley was great about going through and explaining what would be taken out of my security deposit (which honestly wasn't much). The way they do their utilities is a little weird: you pay a flat fee each month and then at the end of your lease you either owe more or get money back. They don't provide you with any update of where you stand throughout the year, which would have been nice, but not a big deal. Since I'm a bit of a treehugger and don't really use my thermostat or overhead lighting, I got a nice little chunk of change back with my security deposit. A nice bonus, indeed!

I've been to JP's many, many times as the semester has progressed and have a better feel for their pros and cons now.

Pros
1) Tasty sandwiches and baked goods (cranberry bread is especially delicious)
2) Atmosphere (comfy couches, ample tables, decent -- if loud -- music)
3) Proximity to ETC

Cons
1) The drinks.  I'm not a coffee drinker and I've been repeatedly unimpressed with their chai (weak) and hot chocolate (sometimes weak and bitter).  The apple cider is middling.  The tessa thai tea is tasty (try saying that three times fast...), but too sweet to be a regular order.
2) Sometimes weak/spotty wifi.

This afternoon I will be going to pick up my deposit from Cooper Brown...I am no longer interested in renting from them for various reasons.  I found a property of theirs online in the Healy Building downtown.  The pictures of the property looked flawless online, but when I went to actually view the property it was filthy and the wooden cabinets were so worn out.  The tile in the shower was scary, and clearly needed to be replaced.  They wanted my deposit which was 45$ higher than the actual rent before my application was even processed, and had no sort of receipt to give me. The condo was listed as having stainless steel appliances, but of course the fridge was steel with black plastic handles and a black microwave.  I won't even get started on the dishwasher.  I was also informed that I would get a confirmation call an hour before the viewing but the agent called me just twenty minutes beforehand.  When I met her there her hair was sopping wet.  I felt this was extremely unprofessional.  I spoke to the receptionist a few days before the viewing and she told me I would not need to have the deposit until after my application had been processed, but of course the agent wanted a check as soon as I saw the place.  These people are confused and have no idea how to make renter/buyer feel confident in their purchase.  My biggest reason for no longer doing business with them is the fact that I told them I needed an immediate move-in and they lolly-gagged with the process because they could not contact my landlord from four years ago, who probably doesn't even remember me! I just told them to forget it and I would be there to pick up my check.  There should not be such a lengthy process for a condo with no parking, black appliances, and a building where young men like to stand out front and socialize.  I would not recommend Cooper Brown to friends or family.

I should be well aware by now that it is common knowledge that coffeehouses don't serve good food. Still, I find this wholly unacceptable at JP's, because given the ample space, comfortable furniture, and sizable patio, people are bound to practically nest there for hours on end; but with the number of signs they have on the walls screaming, "NO OUTSIDE FOOD OR DRINKS," you really have no other choice to satiate your appetite other than to uproot yourself from your seat and just leave. 

I've ordered two of their panini: the margherita (basil, provolone, and tomatoes) and the roast beef (horseradish mayonnaise, arugula and brie). Of the two, the roast beef was far more palatable, but I found that in their panini, the big chunks of toasted bread scratch up my gums way too much. Was this really worth $8? As far as drinks go, I'm a fan of the mint hibiscus tea, but I still hesitate at the thought of shelling out $2.50 for a cup containing more ice than tea.

I still recommend JP's as a decent place to chill, hang out, or study, but I am a fervent supporter of good food and drink at a coffeehouse--because what else is going to keep me there?

A comfortable and affordable spot in Princeton with decent prices and a university-pub ambiance. 

I nearly always get the appetizer order of Quesadillas as a meal. They're huge, affordable, and tasty (the not-so-secret special ingredient is bacon). My husband loves the Bistro burger which comes with a generous topping of Brie.

I can also recommend, as a healthier option, the chili meal, which is flavorful, filling, and comes with salad and garlic bread.
This place isnt that great for dinner or lunch, but for a cheap happy hour and some good mozerella sticks- this is the place to go.  There arent really any other bars in Princeton!

JP's is in a really convenient spot for people who exist in the Engineering area on campus (ahem) and not too much of a trek if you're in the northern part of campus. The parking lot is annoyingly small and reliably full but between the main area inside, the small back room, and the patio you're bound to find a place to sit once you're there. Considering how busy Flightpath and Quacks often are, I'm appreciative of this.

JP's is very hit-or-miss for me. When I walk in, get a chai from a friendly barista, and have a seat, I really enjoy the place. That said, I feel like half the time I have a bad experience. For as good as the chai is when I stay in the shop, it's terrible when I have them make it to-go. It's like they're making a different drink entirely, and certainly not one worth the $4.50 they charge for it.

Some of the staff can be downright unfriendly (is it so hard to call out a drink when it's done, rather than making me stand there wondering if it's my order?) while some of the staff are great.
These guys have been keepin my mornings coffeed up for years! Love the deck and they got beer too!
I've been coming here since I was a kid and am convinced that the food has only improved over the years.  I went to brunch at Winberie's over Memorial Day weekend and was highly impressed.

The coffee here is outta sight.  That's the main reason to go.  They have one of those clover machines, and it's just fantastic.  One of the best cups of coffee in town.  I remember when they switched from their regular drip coffee to that thing and it was like night and day.  The espresso drinks are also great, and the baristas give a damn about pulling a good shot.

Add to this the fact that the place is comfy, they have decent breakfast tacos, great music, and a good university crowd, and it's a great coffeeshop.  The one downside is the food, which is less than inspiring, but does in a pinch.  

One of the other reviewers said this was a "Republican" coffeeshop.  Not sure about that, but if it is, it's the best anti-corporate, quality coffee serving, Gillian Welch playing, tattooed barista hiring Republican coffeeshop I've been to, so there ya go.

Been going here for years during and after college.  Just love the coffee and the vibe.  And they remember your name if you go in enough ;)

Of course it has that youthful energy with so many students, but it's not all students. 

It's mainly the coffee that brings me back despite the lack of available parking.  That's the only downside.  Oh and they don't have a bottomless option.  Oh well

This place has decent food. It doesn't have much going for it besides the fact that it has a nice bar. The service is okay and never exceptional. I feel like you can go anywhere and get equal, if not better food.
Very good pub, but best bet is stick with the pub grub.

This place was my lunchtime haven when I worked at horrible place on campus across the road.  I love all the baristas: the sweethearts of the caffeine world. I have been drinking coffee since I was about 10 and it's very seldom that afternoon caffeine feels like it really gets into ma'blooood, but JP's  heroine coffee does the trick. Plus, it's fun to watch the baristas throw down when someone brings in outside food. Look here, Large...Don't nobody wan' hear your crinklin' and smell your burger while trying to enjoy their premium brews!  Oh, they sell beer, too. Tasty selection with $1 Lonestars at some point in the day. Don't know those hours, though. All you need to know is that this place is just lovely.

I love that we have this starbucks here on campus...I get a pretty complicated beverage ... And for the most part they always get it right...if they don't ....they know to re-make it...before I unleash my wrath...The manager at this location is super sweet he takes the time to really train his student employees...when you get a 5.50 venti cup almost daily you have certain expectations...
